We know that,<br><br>$$\widehat n = {{a \times b} \over {\left| {a \times b} \right|}}$$<br><br>$$a \times b = \left| {\matrix{
   {\widehat i} &amp; {\widehat j} &amp; {\widehat k}  \cr 
   2 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 1  \cr 
   3 &amp; { - 4} &amp; { - 1}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$a \times b = 5\widehat i + 5\widehat j - 5\widehat k$$<br><br>$$\left| {a \times b} \right| = 5\sqrt 3 $$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $$\widehat n = {{5(\widehat i + \widehat j - \widehat k)} \over {5\sqrt 3 }}$$<br><br>$$ = {{\widehat i + \widehat j - \widehat k} \over {\sqrt 3 }}$$

Let $$\Delta  = \left| {\matrix{
   a &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; b &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; c  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = a(bc - 1) - 1(c - 1) + 1(1 - b)$$<br><br>$$ = abc - a - b - c + 2$$<br><br>$$ \because $$ $$\Delta  &gt; 0$$<br><br>$$ \therefore $$ $$abc - a - b - c + 2 &gt; 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow abc + 2 &gt; a + b + c$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow abc + 2 &gt; 3{(abc)^{1/3}}$$<br><br>[$$\because$$ a $$\ne$$ b $$\ne$$ c $$\Rightarrow$$ AM of a, b, c &gt; GM of $$a,b,c \Rightarrow {{a + b + c} \over 3} &gt; {(abc)^{1/3}}$$ $$ \Rightarrow a + b + c &gt; 3{(abc)^{1/3}}$$]<br><br>Now, let $$x = {(abc)^{1/3}}$$, then we have<br><br>$${x^3} + 2 &gt; 3x$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {x^3} - 3x + 2 &gt; 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {(x - 1)^2}(x + 2) &gt; 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow x + 2 &gt; 0$$ [$$\because$$ $${(x - 1)^2} &gt; 0$$]<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow x &gt;  - 2$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {(abc)^{1/3}} &gt;  - 2$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow abc &gt;  - 8$$

We have, $$\left| {\matrix{
   x &amp; { - 3i} &amp; 1  \cr 
   y &amp; 1 &amp; i  \cr 
   0 &amp; {2i} &amp; { - i}  \cr 

 } } \right| = 6 + 11i$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow x( - i + 2) - y( - 3 - 2i) = 6 + 11i$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow 2x + 3y + ( - x + 2y)i = 6 + 11i$$<br><br>On equating real and imaginary parts, on both sides,<br><br>we get $$2x + 3y = 6$$ ..... (i)<br><br>and $$ - x + 2y = 11$$ ..... (ii)<br><br>On solving Eqs. (i) and (ii), we get<br><br>$$x =  - 3$$<br><br>and $$y = 4$$

Given point, P(5, $$-$$6, 7)<br><br>and planes x + y + z = 1<br><br>and 2x $$-$$ y $$-$$ 2z = 3<br><br>Equation of planes in vector form are<br><br>$$r.(\widehat i + \widehat j + \widehat k) = 1$$<br><br>and $$r.(2\widehat i - \widehat j - 2\widehat k) = 3$$<br><br>Since, line is parallel to the given planes.<br><br>$$\therefore$$ Line is perpendicular to the vectors,<br><br>$$\widehat i + \widehat j + \widehat k$$ and $$2\widehat i - \widehat j - 2\widehat k$$<br><br>$$\Rightarrow$$ Line is parallel to the vector<br><br>$$(\widehat i + \widehat j + \widehat k) \times (2\widehat i - \widehat j - 2\widehat k)$$<br><br>$$ = \left| {\matrix{
   {\widehat i} &amp; {\widehat j} &amp; {\widehat k}  \cr 
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   2 &amp; { - 1} &amp; { - 2}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = \widehat i( - 2 + 1) - \widehat j( - 2 - 2) + \widehat k( - 1 - 2)$$<br><br>$$ = \widehat i( - 1) - \widehat j( - 4) + \widehat k( - 3)$$<br><br>$$ = \widehat i + 4\widehat j - 3\widehat k$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ Direction ratios of the line of intersection of the given plane are $$-$$1, 4, $$-$$3 or 1, $$-$$4, 3.

We have,<br><br>$$y = {\cos ^ - }\left( {{{2x} \over {1 + {x^2}}}} \right) = {\pi  \over 2} - {\sin ^{ - 1}}\left( {{{2x} \over {1 + {x^2}}}} \right)$$<br><br>$$ = \left\{ \matrix{
  \left[ {{\pi  \over 2} - (2{{\tan }^{ - 1}}x)} \right],\left| x \right| &lt; 1 \hfill \cr 
  \left[ {{\pi  \over 2} - (\pi  - 2{{\tan }^{ - 1}}x)} \right],x &gt; 1 \hfill \cr 
  \left[ {{\pi  \over 2} - ( - \pi  - 2{{\tan }^{ - 1}}x)} \right],x &lt;  - 1 \hfill \cr}  \right.$$<br><br>$$ = \left\{ \matrix{
  {\pi  \over 2} - 2{\tan ^{ - 1}}x,\left| x \right| &lt; 1 \hfill \cr 
   - {\pi  \over 2} + 2{\tan ^{ - 1}}x,x &gt; 1 \hfill \cr 
  {{3\pi } \over 2} + 2{\tan ^{ - 1}}x,x &lt;  - 1 \hfill \cr}  \right.$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $${{dy} \over {dx}} = \left\{ \matrix{
  {{ - 2} \over {1 + {x^2}}},\left| x \right| &lt; 1 \hfill \cr 
  {2 \over {1 + {x^2}}},x &gt; 1 \hfill \cr 
  {2 \over {1 + {x^2}}},x &lt;  - 1 \hfill \cr}  \right.$$
